    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_304783730" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/304783730" />
    <a title="Diane" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/279256-diane"><img alt="Diane" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1497365060p2/279256.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/304783730?book_show_action=true">Apr 01, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Diane" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Diane" href="/user/show/279256-diane">Diane</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780812981223" href="/book/show/8171197-major-pettigrew-s-last-stand">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/279256-diane?shelf=love-stories">love-stories</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/279256-diane?shelf=british-charm">british-charm</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer304783730" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer13916693945367727142">This is a charming novel set in an English village. It&apos;s the story of Major Pettigrew, retired and a widower, who strikes up a friendship with a Pakistani woman who runs the local shop. The two share a love of books and ideas, and the Major falls in love. But his multicultural romance causes waves in the community and soon he is forced to make a decision.<br/><br/>There is much more going on in the book, including a family battle over heirloom rifles, a social-climbing son and a whole cast of townspeople,</span>
  <span id="freeText13916693945367727142" style="display:none">This is a charming novel set in an English village. It's the story of Major Pettigrew, retired and a widower, who strikes up a friendship with a Pakistani woman who runs the local shop. The two share a love of books and ideas, and the Major falls in love. But his multicultural romance causes waves in the community and soon he is forced to make a decision.<br /><br />There is much more going on in the book, including a family battle over heirloom rifles, a social-climbing son and a whole cast of townspeople, but the best parts of the story involve the Major and how he reacts to these changes in his life. Simonson's writing is very insightful and humorous; many passages made me laugh. I've never lived in an English village, but the descriptions in this book are exactly how I imagined it.<br /><br />Some have compared this book to Jane Austen's novels, and it's true that Austen fans will probably appreciate this novel of social manners and late-in-life romance. But the story stands on its own merits. <br /><br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="13916693945367727142" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

